The Huawei P30 Pro has changed all that. Its brilliant. Far superior to my iPhone X. Forget the fact that the pixel resolution is inferior to a lot of the competition, the screen is fantastic. Transferring files e.g. music, videos is easy thanks to their HiSuite app. Only one speaker but it is sufficiently loud and clear if you're not using earbuds. Other than a couple of garden snaps, I haven't even explored the camera yet, which is reportedly its real strong point. I would have gone for the P40 Pro but the lack of google services frightened me off. A big thumbs up to Livewire Telecom also. Firstly their low price made it hard to resist. The Samsung ISOCELL HP3 SuperZoom Sensor and SuperOIS enhances the overall camera performance.    *[Fast Charging Technology] :- Courtesy to the 100 W SUPERVOOC charge with GaN, you can quickly charge your smartphone and get on with your day. It has up to 38 layers of charging protection, power efficiency, and quick charging that provides 100% charge in about 26 minutes.

[{'Reviewer': 'The power of dreams', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in Spain on 7 May 2024', 'Review': 'Después de .Miran tanto no hay nada como un clásico y no tiene nada que envidiar a los sistemas más avanzados y caros bueno lo siguiente

Cooper', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 24 December 2023', 'Review': "I resisted getting a smartphone for a long time, largely because the people I know who have them have endless trouble with theirs. However, I was using a 4G-wifi device which was costing £24 a month for 30GB, and I realised the savings I could make in a year by using a phone as a hotspot would pay for a smartphone within a year, so I read hundreds of reviews for different phones and settled on this one as the most affordable one that lacked complaints about unreliability issues. I bought a 50GB SIM to use in it costing £11 a month (£10 initially). A review here gave me the confidence that this should work as it was from someone who was already using this model of phone as a hotspot with the same network. The hotspot works beautifully, and it's much faster at getting the data in, so it now allows my computer to play youtube videos without the picture freezing repeatedly.Everything else about the phone is thus a bonus as my main need was to connect my computer to the internet through it, but I was looking for a phone that wouldn't cut out during calls or do bizarre things with the display to make the keyboard and speakerphone hard to access during calls - the kind of problems that plague the smartphones of other members of my family, and this one did not disappoint as it just does the job properly without complications.I've never been interested in computer games, but there was one exception, and it would test the phone maximally: I was hoping to find a formula 1 game, and I settled on Monoposto which it handles with ease, so I've spent a month on the Netherlands circuit (having turned off all the driving assistance). My only complaint is that if the battery level hits 20%, it flashes up a huge warning message which makes driving on impossible. Another issue is that it's hard to hold the device without occasionally hitting the brake by accident with the skin of the left hand bulging round the side onto the edge of the screen unless you turn the phone upside down to put the wider margin there, but then the screen keeps dimming unless you search for a setting to turn that off - I think the problem's caused by a proximity sensor, but it can be resolved if you find the right menu.The other apps that attracted my attention all work on it too: Stellarium, electronic compass, GPS, a synthesiser (the speakers are good and loud without distortion), instrument tuner (because I make flutes) - everything I want works on it just fine. The camera does a good job too - I've just been testing it on nacreous clouds and got good results after finding an exposure control (a long touch on the screen brings it up), though nothing like as good as what you see directly with your eyes. I'd put a picture in here if I could transfer it easily to this computer, but I don't have an easy way to do that, and connecting it with a cable doesn't appear to enable me to access its files, perhaps because they're on the internal storage rather than a micro-SD card - that's something which I need to investigate further, but it may just be that I don't know enough about how to use it. Regardless of that, all my doubts about smartphones have been blown away by this one. I can't know if it's the best one in its approximate price range though - there's a Samsung costing £30 to 40 more which was my second choice, but whether it's better or not I cannot tell as I'm more than happy with this one and am certainly keeping it.Edit: Further information about its capability. It can screen record (i.e. video what's happening on the screen including the audio and/or microphone input), and it can do this while running that formula one game with smooth results - I wasn't expecting it to have the processing power needed for that, but it handles it fine.

Read more"}, {'Reviewer': 'Hambones500', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 6 June 2024', 'Review': "All said in the adverts really - The 30w charger is European but I expected that - it won't be nicked by other family members, lol.I was researching about other reviews comparing it to the Moto G54, apparently another great phone to consider; I have confirmed this phone has wifi-6 for futureproof, not the G54 I think, but its more powerful chip gets a bit of stick for being battery-hungry with the same decent 5000mAh battery, so I did a comparison with my old phone, a Redmi 8t that I was always happy had a good battery - playing youtube simultaneously, the 8t uses about three times (3x!) more percentage battery per hour - so the G73 battery absolutely smoked it, and for battery-happiness the G73 gets a big thumbs-up from me.
Read more"}, {'Reviewer': 'Algoy', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in Spain on 10 December 2023', 'Review': 'Terminal que ofrece tres años de actualizaciones de seguridad, actualización a android 14 asegurada, procesador que puntúa 500.000 en antutu, 8gb de ram y 256 de almacenamiento, Radio FM (casi imposible de ver en gamas medias, no hablemos de altas), buena batería de 5000mah y por 179€ que me costó.Poco que decir, es cierto que su pvp era 299, que dado su construcción en plástico no hubiera pagado, pero al precio conseguido en Black Friday se le perdona (tampoco está mal construido aunque sea plástico, no hay ruidos o crujidos al cogerlo, es muy ergonómico).En rendimiento, vuela. Vengo de un Nokia 8 con un Snapdragon 835 (lo más alto de 2017-2018) y es que le deja en pañales, a pesar de tener 6gb de ram y 128gb, tampoco iba cojo.Sobre la conectividad, Wifi 6 que se nota muchísimo si tienes router moderno y conexión decente, se instalan las aplicaciones en un suspiro, sin calentarse el terminal. Bluetooth 5.3, NFC (permite el pago con tarjeta usando Google Wallet / Pay) y Radio FM, sin consumir datos, utilizando unos auriculares conectados a su jack 3.5mmSobre pantalla y sonido...a ver, vengo de una pantalla 2k 5.3" IPS de muy alta calidad, y aún así no noto gran bajón. La resolución es FHD+ y los colores se ven bastante naturales incluso en el modo saturado. Sobre el brillo, pues menos que mi Nokia 8 (700 nits) así que supongo que ronda los 450-500 (suficiente para uso incluso exterior aunque no continuado)El lector de huellas es muy rápido abriendo el móvil y de momento aún no me ha fallado ni una vez.Si que noto cosas que no me han gustado, como que no lo puedas apagar, si pulsar apagar sale el asistente de Google. Solo hay que desactivar este comportamiento en Ajustes y ya será "normal"; pero yo viniendo de Android 9 pues estaba algo perdido.Hablando del Sistema, Android 13 casi puro, sin capa de personalización propia de Motorola, mucho mejor de cara a una buena longevidad del terminal, ya que muchas veces con los años, se actualizan las capas de aquella manera y se arrastra que da gusto. Muy contento salvo con el bloatware que trae (Glovo, tik tok, Opera y alguna más) y que a veces al actualizarlo le dan por volver. También decir como apuntaba al inicio que tiene asegurada la actualización a Android 14, lo que se agradece.Por último decir que trae un cable usb-c a usb-c y un cargador compatible con carga rápida de 30W, ambos muy bien construidos. Esto se agradece muchísimo, ya que la mayoría de terminales de gama media ya ni los traen.
Read more'}]

reviews:
[{'Reviewer': 'Jason Darragh', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 28 March 2024', 'Review': "If you are looking for a budget mobile with decent specs, not too big then this is an excellent option.I am not a fan of most mobiles as at 6.5ins upwards they are like mini tablets. Plus they take up ample room in the pocket. At 6.28ins this is a great compromise especially coming from a smaller Google Pixel 3a like me.Motorola have included a case and super quick 68w charger in the box, thank you for that! The handset is very light, thin and feels great in the hand.Upon set up there are a few additional apps that can be uninstalled but Motorola have provided a pretty clean version of Android. There are a good amount of options to tailor the Edge 30 Neo to your preferred style.Spec wise the Snapdragon 695 is nowhere near top end but for apps, browsing and light gaming is more than enough. The Dolby Atmos speaker is excellent and goes loud.Camera is okay for the price point however I don't purchase a mobile based on its camera.I think for the price this is an excellent budget mobile and for my requirements it is ideal.
Read more"}, {'Reviewer': 'Renata', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in Spain on 8 October 2023', 'Review': 'Motorola Edge 30 Neo chipset 5G de procesador Snapdragon 695, 8/128 GB, Doble SIM, Black 👍
Read more'}, {'Reviewer': 'Leonardo', 'Rating': '2.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in Italy on 6 October 2023', 'Review': 'Nulla da dire
Read more'}, {'Reviewer': 'nemo78', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in France on 24 March 2023', 'Review': "Pour mon usage (android auto, waze, spotify, appli pro) il est parfait, fluide et réactif.Reconnaissance faciale & digitale performante.La charge rapide est un vrai plus.La qualité de l'écran est excellente.Je recommande sans réserves.
Read more"}, {'Reviewer': 'Tom Hamblett', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 7 May 2023', 'Review': "Beautiful little phone, the fantastic upgrade from my G7 power that my huge G60s wasn't! 8GB ram is definitely what I was missing, smaller oled screen and efficient CPU mean the battery life is still good whilst 1080 resolution means websites etc work properly. No need to charge overnight, charges so quickly it's done by the time I've had a shower and breakfast although you could put it on a wireless pad next to your bed which would take all night at 5w and if it moves and doesn't charge overnight the 68w charger it comes with means that's not a problem, you can easily put a days worth in it before leaving the house.Out of the box it didn't want to do face recognition and the selfie camera seemed to have a ridiculously yellow filter on it but next morning in daylight it worked ok and still unlocked in artificial light that night, there was an update so possibly that had a bug fix in it as I just tried the selfie camera in pitch darkness and using the screen border to light me up the colour seemed fine.I've had no problem with the fingerprint scanner and under the screen is certainly better than on the back but I still feel built into the power button on the side like the wife's old Razer was the best place and I can't understand why more phones don't do that! (Yes I went back to a G7 from a superfast Razer with 4k screen resolution because it munched through its battery in half a day with light use!)
Read more"}]

Title: Samsung Galaxy Z Flip4 5G (Bora Purple, 8GB RAM, 256GB Storage) Without Offers
Description:
About this item    Style and function that fits in your pocket. It's a pocket-sized statement piece. Small but mighty when folded, this phone is compact enough to fit in your palm, but leaves a big impression with sleek, hazy colors that match your vibe.    Our toughest Samsung Galaxy foldables ever. The world’s first water-resistant foldable smartphones have never been so strong.2 These scratch-defying devices are our toughest ever with exclusive Corning Gorilla Glass Victus+ on the outside and the super durable Ultra Thin Glass on the inside. And the hinge is protected by Armor Aluminum — our toughest aluminum frame.    Cameras that capture life with new perspective.Take advantage of this camera phone’s agile angles. Quick Shot lets you shoot a selfie right from the Cover Screen, even allowing a ratio change to show you the full frame before you shoot. Or unfold and take position with FlexCam holding up the camera so you can get a hands-free group shot or selfie at mind-blowing perspectives.    Faster charging speed. Longer battery life.An upgraded 4nm processor works with the long-lasting 3700mAh (typical) battery to power through the hours. When it's low, plug in for Super Fast Charging, or bypass the cord with Fast Wireless Charging 2.0 With all that power to spare, you can even share a charge with your friend or your earbuds with Wireless PowerShare.    See what's important in a glance with Cover Screen. The 4.82 cm (1.9-inch) Cover Screen now gives you even more information and control.

reviews:
[{'Reviewer': 'Mengo', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in Germany on 11 January 2023', 'Review': 'Bin echt zufrieden mit dem Moto g52, ich hatte es hier in einer Actions Woche für knapp 180 Euronen erworben.Klar darf man es jetzt nicht mit den Spitzenmodellen vergleichen und doch kann es da teilweise mithalten.Erwähnenswert ist da sicher das OLED Display, mit starkem Kontrast tollem schwarz und darum auch mit mit einer hervorragenden Lesbarkeit. Geschützt ist es mit Kratzsicherem Glas so das eine Schutzfolie nicht nötig ist. Besonders ist auch der 5000 mAh Akku er gibt dem Gerät eine wirklich lange Laufzeit (bei meiner Nutzung ca. 3 Tage)und wird mit dem starken Ladegerät in kürzester Zeit wieder aufgepumpt ( von 20 auf gut 80% in 15-20Min.)Auf der Softwareseite läuft am 11.01. 2023 Android 12, hab gelesen 13 soll kommen. Aber alles läuft sehr flott und funktioniert gut. Ich bin Anhänger von "Android One" das gibt's bei Motorola leider nicht mehr aber es ist noch nah dran, mit den 3 nicht deinstallierbaren Moto Apps kann ich leben :-)Ich mag das Design, das Gerät wirkt wertig, man merkt zwar das die Rückseite aus Plastik ist aber man sieht es nicht, außerdem ist eine Schutzhülle im Lieferumfang. Damit ists eh egal.Bemerkenswert ist noch der An/Aus Schalter rechts am Gerät, dort ist ein Fingerabdrucksensor integriert, das  funktioniert sehr gut und ist beeindruckend schnell.Zur Fotoqualität, ich finde das gebotene ist echt OK, ist besser als ich erwartete :)Bleibt noch zu erwähnen die fehlende benachrichtigungs Led, es gibt keine! ich habe mich da mittlerweile dran gewöhnt, meistens hat man das Telefon ja dabei und bekommt Nachrichten mit wenn sie reinkommen, weil es vibriert und das Display aufleuchtet, wenn nicht braucht man es nur kurz berühren, dann wird sie Angezeigt.Von mir sind das 5 Sternchen für das Moto52. Description:
About this item    Featuring Qualcomm's most advanced mobile platform, Snapdragon 8 Gen 1, the device sets the bar for next-generation computing with a cutting-edge 4nm technology process. While the GPU capabilities have increased 30% in terms of graphics rendering, and energy efficiency has increased 25%, Xiaomi 12 is capable of delivering unprecedented levels of performance and power efficiency over its predecessor    Xiaomi 12 boasts a 50MP pro-grade main camera, a 13MP ultra-wide angle camera, and a 5MP telemacro camera. To complement the impressive hardware,the device is also equipped with Xiaomi’s advanced AI algorithm across a wide range of scenarios to enable cinematic capabilities with professional special effects and creative options including Xiaomi ProFocus, One-click AI cinema, etc.    Xiaomi 12 features a 6.28-inch AMOLED screen with an FHD+ resolution of 2400 x 1080, provides over 68 billion colors, and comes with TrueColor display delivered by professional color calibration. The device also supports a 120Hz AdaptiveSync refresh rate and up to 480Hz touch sampling rate, ensuring an incredibly smooth entertainment experience. Featuring Dolby Vision and HDR 10+, users can enjoy ultra-vivid images backed by incredible brightness, contrast, and colors full of details.    This immersive visual experience is also complemented by an outstanding audio experience. Powered by a pair of symmetrical speakers, Xiaomi 12 boasts cinematic-grade stereo sound delivered with SOUND BY Harman Kardon, and supports Dolby Atmos    Hard as it is to believe, Xiaomi 12 packs a 4,500mAh battery in its extremely compact body, thanks to upgraded high-power density battery material, to offer all-day use and life free from battery anxiety. For a better battery life, Xiaomi AdaptiveCharge - Xiaomi’s smart charging algorithm, works in tandem to learn users’ overnight charging behavior and optimizing accordingly. Xiaomi 12 also supports Xiaomi 67W wired and 50W wireless turbo charging.Included components: usb cable.    
 ›  See more product details
reviews:
[{'Reviewer': 'J Magee', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 2 April 2023', 'Review': 'I've had the phone for under a week so this is an initial review. I bought the phone in the Amazon Spring sale for a very good price, almost half of its original cost.The phone seems great. It comes well packaged with lots of accessories including the appropriate 67W fast charger and cable, clear back case and it even comes with some earphones, but strangely these are 3.5mm not usb-c and they don't provide an adapter. Some reviews claim no earphones were provided but as can be seen in the photos they are in a boxed section next to the usb cable.The phone itself seems well built. It has a nice curved screen with a pre applied screen protector on it and the back is a nice frosted glass. I bought the blue version and it looks nice. The screen is great. Good colours, 120Hz refresh rate and up to around 1000nits brightness so it is bright enough to use outside on a sunny day and great for HDR content. The screen is also not too large at 6.28". The underdisplay fingerprint reader works great, not had any issues with it.The phone has good speakers with nice stereo Harman Kardon sound. They get quite loud and sound well balanced with no distortion.The cameras are also quite good. Nice vibrant colours with lots of detail. I've included a photo I took in bright daylight and the light and contrast have been handled well and not overblown. The ultrawide camera is decent too. The only downside is there is no dedicated telephoto zoom lens, with just a 2X crop from the main sensor. There is a macro camera which seems fine. The selfie camera is ok too.The software is up to date with Android 13. All apps work well but i would recommend turning off miui battery saver on some apps like email and messenger to prevent missed notifications. One downside with the phone is the battery life. The battery life is OK but it only just about gets me through the day. Luckily it charges very quick with the included 67W charger. It fills up in around 40mins.Overall I'd definitely recommend this phone at the reduced price. Excellent value for money!
Read more'}, {'Reviewer': 'Vince Marsters', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 9 October 2022', 'Review': "This has been one of the best phones I have used for a long time. It has a large screen which is clear and bright, with the added advantage of high refresh rate capabilities. This does come at a price of higher battery consumption, but the default dynamic setting is great for giving a longer battery life where high refresh is not required. The screens rounded sides is a bit 'marmite' as many do not like these, but I prefer them - a bit love or hate though. In the box you do get a factory fitted screen protector and a clear gel case - so you can protect the phone from day one without spending any more.The fingerprint reader is in-screen at the bottom. For me it is well placed and works that fast, I hardly even get to press on the screen.Processor and memory capability is great as it comes with a Snapdragon 8 Gen 1 and 8GB ram. MIUI can also use up to 3GB of storage as ram extension when space is available - giving 11GB ram in normal use. The huge 256GB storage means the chances of running out of space is reduced too.SIM card wise, you get a dual SIM slot with the cards fitting back-to-back - no eSIM here. The phone works well with a single card in either slot too.Software wise, MIUI is a good Android based operating system. The current MIUI 13 is based on Android 12 and Xiaomi have said they will provide OS updates until MIUI15 and at least 4 years of OS security updates. Experience shows the security updates come at intervals between 1-3 months. This is a shame as flagship devices should really come with monthly updates. Many of the default apps are Google versions (dialer, messages, browser & pay/wallet) and there are a few MI specific versions.I have had a couple of applications that didn't work properly when first installed (pushed from my old phone using the device transfer capability). Removing and reinstalling has fixed these so I suspect there was a problem during the device transfer.A very nice capability is dual app - this allows you to be logged into an app with two accounts when ordinarily the app does not allow it. You can also have a 'second space' which gives a semi-hidden second instance of MIUI - great if you need to hide something from the primary space, although I found this did cause some lag in the phone when I tried it (don't need it but wanted to see what it was all about).Camera quality for me has been great. I have been able to take photos from portraits up to wide landscapes. It doesn't have a lot of the image processing of Google but for my needs, it is more than good enough to replace a dedicated camera most of the time.I have one issue with the camera app though - when it sees a QR code you get a little symbol to read it. When it is a link, it doesn't always work as planned - sometimes it is a web link that must be copied (my energy supplier uses one for setting up one of the devices they give and that uses a weblink that their app opens but it doesn't work with the Xiaomi camera app).Overall, I recommend this phone for anyone looking for a decent flagship phone without the four-figure price tag. It is a fully rounded flagship phone with long support and a decent OS.
Read more"}, {'Reviewer': 'LCL', 'Rating': '4.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 24 January 2024', 'Review': "Oddly not as good as the 10. I never had any issues with the 10, great phone. This 12, crashes more, a few times a week. The battery isn't quite as good as the 10. The camera is okay what they did improve was photo editing. The erase function I am really happy with. I think it's the best thing on the phone. It's quite small. I'd prefer bigger. But for the price. As the 13 ultra wasn't available in the UK I got this. Better than the Google pixel. Screen colours are good. Speakers are fine. No headphone jack. No real issues except occasionally an app will need to be reopened. It's not exceptional. It's mostly okay.
Read more"}, {'Reviewer': 'James127', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 28 September 2023', 'Review': 'I have owned and loved  a Huawei P20 pro for 4 years, and have struggled to find a good upgrade. This fits the bill. About the same size - a bit taller and thinner, but fits in the hand perfectly. The screen is better, everything is faster, the battery is day and a half with fast wired and wireless charging and the cameras are good (but without optical zoom). The screen and sound are really good. MIUI has its quirks but most can be overcome. Everything connects well - Bluetooth headphones particularly and the transfer from one phone to another was quick and easy. All in all a great Upgrade without breaking the bank. A happy custoner

Camera is wonderful, the phone itself is quite fast, doesn't lag, features a lot of space. There is a lot of advertisement and commercial functions that you cannot get rid of on it. It doesn't get in the way of everyday use, but is still pretty annoying.
Read more"}, {'Reviewer': 'paco', 'Rating': '3.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in Spain on 25 December 2022', 'Review': 'Te llega bien presentado dentro de una caja de color amarillo con el nombre del móvil serigrafiado y con el logo de 5G. El que yo he probado es el de color “sunrise blue”, porque buscaba algo diferente, su aspecto varía en función de como le da la luz. Es un color  queda muy bien si no buscas un color sobrio.Además del móvil, la caja incluye un cargador de 33 W y una funda de plástico de color ahumado. Un paquete bastante completo, teniendo en cuenta que hoy día muchos móviles vienen incluso sin cargador.Se trata de un móvil grande, de 6,6 pulgadas, aunque no es demasiado pesado para su tamaño, no llega a los 200 g sin funda.La pantalla tiene luces y sombras, es Full HD y, aunque es IPS, se ve bien, fluida con sus  hasta 120 Hz y con buenos ángulos de visión. Sin embargo, le veo dos cuestiones que no me han gustado demasiado:- Por su precio creo que podría haber venido con una pantalla Amoled.- El brillo máximo se queda corto en días soleados, sólo llega a 600 nits.Respecto a la seguridad, tiene un sensor de huellas en el lateral (en el botón de encendido) que va muy bien. El reconocimiento facial también funciona perfectamente.Cuenta con Jack 3.5 para poderle poner auriculares con cable. Sin embargo, para oirlo sin auriculares, sólo tiene un altavoz, se escucha bien, pero en su precio hay otras alternativas con dos altavoces para poderlo escuchar en estéreo.Viene con un procesador Snapdragon 695, que me ha sorprendido para bien, va más  fluido de lo que esperaba, incluso para un uso moderado en juegos. Cuenta con NFC para poder pagar con tarjeta.En el momento de la reseña, ya se me ha actualizado a Android 13, bajo la capa de personalización Realme UI 4.0. La capa va muy bien, de hecho es una de las capas de personalización más cómodas que he probado.Tiene una batería de 5000 mAh, con un uso normal me aguanta más de un día de uso. La carga rápida no es de las mejores que puedes encontrar, sólo llega a 33 W.Las cámaras son, aparentemente buenas en cuanto a los números que ofrecen, pero después de probarlas, es uno de los apartados que más me ha decepcionado de este móvil. Tiene 3 cámaras traseras en total: Una cámara principal de 64 megapixels, un gran angular de 8 megapixels y un sensor macro. En fotografía diurna, con buena luz cumple. Sin embargo, la calidad del gran angular y de la fotografía nocturna las he encontrado muy flojas. Con el modo noche mejora algo, pero en su rango de precio hay cámaras mejores. El vídeo tampoco es uno de sus fuertes, he podido grabar a una resolución máxima de 1080 a 30 fps. La cámara para selfies también la he encontrado bastante mejorable.A modo de resumen, como puntos positivos puedo mencionar:- Diseño bastante bonito, aunque en plástico.- El procesador hace que el móvil vaya más fluido de lo que esperaba.- Tiene una pantalla de 120 Hz.- La capa de Realme UI hace que tengas una buena experiencia de uso.- Batería que cumple, supera el día de duración.Como cuestiones a mejorar, puedo destacar las siguientes:- La pantalla no es Amoled, y el brillo se queda corto los días de sol.- Sólo tiene un altavoz.- La fotografía, en general decepciona, cumple sólo con buena luz. El video y la fotografía nocturna la he encontrado muy mejorable.A modo de conclusión, no puedo recomendar este móvil en su precio habitual (por encima de 300€). Sin embargo, si lo encuentras en una buena oferta  puedes tenerlo en cuenta si buscas un teléfono equilibrado y para ti lo principal no es la fotograría.

reviews:
[{'Reviewer': 'K.', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 3 May 2021', 'Review': "Came from a Moto G6 that was about 2 years and a couple months old.  The battery in that phone just gave up and wouldn't get me through the day.  Otherwise, loved that phone dearly and have been a huge fan of Motorola. When looking this time, I couldn't get over some of the cons of the G8 plus and the size of the G9. Why do all phones have to be so damn big? This Realme 7 pro is big but the width is OK to handle with 1 hand and it feels lighter than I expected. This is my first time with Facial Recognition, which I really like. The fingerprint scanner works OK, like 90%+ success rate but the Motorola physical one was better - faster, more reliable. Don't know why the passcode has to be so long but other than that, most of the I use facial recognition. It's great but doesn't work well with masks and definitely not with sunglasses.  So when you are outside, on the go or in a store, you need to rely on the fingerprint, which as I said, is decent. 2nd note is the power and volume split. I actually don't like it even though both sets of buttons are in an OK location. Too often, I pick up my phone and take a screenshot.  It can be hard to tell if my phone is upside down from feel alone.  Again, the Motorola was generally better, although I find these buttons to have a better click and feel on the Realme.  The UI is perfect for me as I prefer the sleek, stock Android.  There are a few nice touches from Realme.  I like that I was able to set my back and home buttons like Android 8 and 9.  The back button to the right was one of the dumbest things I've seen.  I haven't tried the Android 10 swipe to back.  So whatever.  Performance and screen clarity are great.  The screen is super bright outside.  The auto brightness works OK, maybe slightly on the dim side, which is good for battery life.  The phone is quick to respond though not like a huge step from my previous phone. The camera is superb.  My wife has had a Huawei 10 pro for a couple years and that thing took photos that blew away my Moto G6.  This Realme phone tops hers.  I'm really exited to take the phone on a proper trip and do some night time shots.  We had a walk in the dusk and it blew hers away - which we thought was otherwise very good at night.  The battery life on a standard day only goes down to 65% or 70%, which is great considering my old G6 wouldn't make it through a full day. It lost 20-25% capacity over the years.  I've now taken the Realme 7 pro on 2 long day trips involving heavy navigation, searches, calls, general surfing and lots of screen time with guided walks. Both days it got to 20% by the time I was safely back at home and late at night.  I trust that most heavy days won't be an issue.  However, my G6 for two years with it's 3000 mAhr battery would basically do the same.  So this Realme 7 with the 5000 mAhr battery clearly uses more power but feels like it should be solid for a couple years, provided I get the same battery life out of the device. Calls are good. Sound through the 2 speakers is nice, clear.  The minimum volume on youtube videos and navigation is fine.  But the minimum volume on the alarm is annoyingly too high.  If I'm setting it at the first audible setting, and it's shocking me awake, who the hell is using the rest of the volume?  Overall, it might not sound like I'm impressed. However, I actually am impressed with this phone. It was the smart buy - huge value, great price, upgrades where it counts over my G6. If I could do it over, I would buy it again. I am an engineer and am picky. I want perfection.  This is not it but it's totally a great phone.
Read more"}, {'Reviewer': 'Morgan', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 11 February 2021', 'Review': 'I am often surprised at how I get used to using a fast and responsive phone. That point was made clear to me as my main phone needed to be replaced and I had to use my backup one. My goodness did I notice the difference.With some hesitation I decided to buy this RealMe Pro 7 phone, am I glad that I did.The AMOLED screen is lovely, the blacks are deep and inky, without loosing detail. The rest of the colours and punchy without being overly saturated. You do have quite a bit of control on how it looks within the settings.The responsiveness of the phone is impressive, as is the 8GB of memory it comes with.The camera is excellent in my opinion, with photos and video being great and clear. The night mode for the camera is very good, lifting otherwise dark scenes to be a most useful image. You do have to have a steady hand if using the night Mode feature, but it is worth it.I have installed a 256GB card, with the 4k video capabilities and the size of the photo images I can see that being most useful.I have included four photos with this review, the first two being the front and back of the phone. The phone comes with its own Gel clear case which is adequate, you can see that in photo 3. It fits well and protects the phone, It also has a plastic screen protector on, obviously well fitted.Also in photo 3 you can see the fast charger and rather chunky charging cable. I have not used mine as yet as I have the equivalent chargers available. The phone does charge fast...!In the 4th photo you can see some of the specs of the phone. Maybe I missed i but I could not see the overall RAM listed in the specs. You can see that it comes with 8GB of RAM.The overall feel and use of the phone is very pleasing. When I first powered it on I was informed, after going through the setup, that there is a software update. That is over 3GB in size. That installed fine.Even though it is Android there are some very nice custom options for the phone which can be found under "Additional Settings".This phone, albeit only a few days old at the time of this review, has been a good choice and I would struggle to downgrade the five stars that I have been happy enough to award it. .I do hope that this review has helped you.Happy shopping 😊
Read more'}, {'Reviewer': 'shhwab', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 8 November 2020', 'Review': "This is a very good phone... My last phone was an Huawei mate pro 10. A brilliant phone with everything I needed. However, I decided it was time for a change so I bought a Samsung m31. On paper the Samsung seemed very good. In practice it was horrible! It was sluggish, crashed, no aptxhd and poor in general.I searched for a while for a phone to fill all my needs; amoled screen, fast enough and graphics to play call of duty, aptxhd (I use my phone mainly for music, tidal and b&w px5 headphones) I also wanted fast charge and good battery... The realme 7 pro offers all these things and has 8gb ram and 128gb internal memory (Samsung had 6gb/64gb). Anyway, the realme came and straight out of the box it felt, looked and just seemed better than the samsung. I quickly turned it on and it just worked, all my programs etc copied over and in 10 mins it was ready.... The phone is a delight and the addition of aptx adaptive is superb... Not many phones support this. Tbh I didn't think it had aptxhd, but I can assure you it does...note: the Dolby Atmos is on as standard and it ruins the sound...I plugged it in and watched the battery charge in real time... The charging cable is a beast and the phone doesn't seem to warm up too much whilst charging.I tried the camera which was great, but better after an auto firmware update. The main camera does not smooth out noise as much as the Samsung, which seems less.noisy despite being the same sensor. However it's at the cost of detail. Personally I prefer a bit of noise and more detail. After all we can always use Photoshop to handle noise...The speakers are very good, providing a detailed 3d sound experience whilst playing games or movies. Not the loudest (as loud as my old mate pro 10) but more than enough for intimate use.The screen is great, vibrant, very sharp and clear... Better than the Samsung screen.Basically, I cannot find any real issues! If I was to mention one negative point, it would be the finger print sensor in the screen. It works well enough, but it's quite slow compared to pretty much all normal finger print unlocking phones. Luckily the face recognition works very well! Even in low light.Ok... I have waffled enough. I may add na update after I have used the phone for a few weeks...
Read more"}, {'Reviewer': 'Dave C', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 17 May 2021', 'Review': "Awesome underrated phone!I've owned mainly Motorola android phones in the past, but I fancied trying an underdog brand, and I'm really happy.I'm picky, I'm an engineer, I tried the Poco X3 NFC prior to picking this phone and the realme fits my needs very well. The X3 went back.Pros:Call quality - excellent, no distortion, speaker is plenty loud enough and can be made quiet for discreet calls. Stereo speakers for hands-free calls are clear, loud and don't vibrate the plastic case, unlike the X3.Bloat - there is very little put on top of the stock android build, which I like, but I miss some of the extra visual enhancements offered by the X3. It doesn't have ads.Screen - crisp, ultra clear and buttery smooth. This is very good and well worth the money. I had very slight lag when scrolling with my thumb on the X3, but no problem on the realme. The always on feature is really nice that reminds me of flip phones of old.Camera - The 64Mp camera is good, but there is a slight lag in taking a picture when on its highest setting (64). I'm sure this is just software and will be resolved in a future update or using a different camera app.Battery - haven't tried getting 2 days out of a charge yet, but I think it would be just about possible. Charger is awesome. Went from 40% to 95% in 10 mins. Battery on X3 is better, but weighs more, and this phone is nice and light.Buttons - didn't think I would like the volume buttons on the left, but they work well and the positioning makes sense.Cons:Not a great deal really, wish it had a bigger battery and more UI customisation, the X3 poco launcher feels more polished on that front. Waiting for Android 11 release.Fingerprint scanner isn't going to be as good as a physical scanner mounted on the side, but it works ok and the face recognition works very well, so not really a problem.If you are in any doubt about buying this, don't be. It's a excellent phone with a great set of features rivalling more expensive ones. My wife wants one now :)Update (after using a few weeks): battery life easily manages 2 days. However, no sign of android 11. Received 2 android 10 updates. Realme is really lacking customer support - but overall a fantastic phone for the money.
Read more"}, {'Reviewer': 'Amazon Customer', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 3 January 2021', 'Review': "Had to return first on as wasn't getting a signal at all.  I left it a couple of weeks before buying a second one as I wondered if it was the best phone as we are in a poor signal area.  Having looked at the eyewatering price of S10 and S20's to replace my S7 I gambled and ordered another 7Pro whilst it was on special offer.  Glad to say this one is great, signal working as well as any other phone here. screen great and is easy to use. Its got the Samsung type sidebar see on expensive models.  The operating system is simple and easy to use which is just as well as there is no manual.  For me I wanted a good battery life and room for a SD card. This has both, the battery lasted over 48 hours with light use last week (my Samsung S7 was only lasting about 12 hours) and the Dart charge is fantastic so quick.  The phone takes up to 256gb card too so loads of room for photos.  Size wise I was worried it would be too big for me as my S7 is quite small but it is not an issue. Overall the screen is bigger but the frame is small and thin.  It feels light and comfortable in my small hands.  The edges are straight and not curved, for me this is a plus as the screen protectors fall off the curved screens easier.On the down side there is little available on the Realme uk store website in the way of cases or spare chargers/usb leads.  Don't try to charge the phone with a normal usb lead as the Dart charge wont kick in.  However I have found the the Oppo Super Vooc charger is identical to the Realme (including part number, I believe that Realme was part of Oppo at one stage) and the Super Vooc leads work as well,  Oppo they also do a great fast car charger.  Make sure you get the genuine Oppo stuff though.  The Oppo uk site isn't too bad on price, I also brought spare Oppo usb leads on Amazon which work well.  It does not support wireless chargingOverall this is a great phone at the price,  its not 5g but as we often don't even get 4g or even 3g in some areas around here that wasn't important for me.  You will be hard pushed to find another phone at £220 to meet this ones specs.
Read more"}]

[{'Reviewer': 'PaulTez', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 5 June 2020', 'Review': "I've had this device for just over a week now and I am very impressed. Total garbage. So if, like me, any time you go somewhere with the remotest possibility of wanting to take a photograph you take a proper camera with you, it's pointless to spend a lot more money on a smartphone just to get a better camera module. Incidentally, if you do want a phone with a great camera, I currently recommend the Pixel 4a 5G or Pixel 5 - they take really nice photos, even if you have no idea what you're doing. Which leads me to the camera on the X50 Pro 5G - image quality is average, responsiveness is excellent thanks to the phone's fast processor, and that's all I have to say about that. As for the rest of the phone - wow! It's right up there with flagship phones that cost two to three times as much. The screen is beautiful - the 90hz OLED panel is a joy to behold. Some people don't like the double selfie camera notch, but until invisible in-screen cameras are the norm, a notch is a notch. Performance is great - whatever you ask it to do the processor scoffs at your puny demands and responds in a flash. Sound quality is good for a smartphone - I mostly listen to spoken word on the phone speakers and it's lovely not to have sound so tinny it makes your ears hurt. The big battery and rapid charging mean that I plug the phone in once a day, just before going to bed, and the battery is full in less than half-an-hour. Even with a lot of screen-time and live wallpaper running, it would be unusual for the battery to drop below 20%. My favourite feature of the phone is the in-screen fingerprint scanner. It's by far the fastest such scanner I've come across and is so reliable that anything that can be secured with biometrics on my phone is now unlocked via the scanner. Twigden', 'Rating': '4.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 18 July 2020', 'Review': "This is a strange review really, as I love this phone in so many ways, yet am choosing to return it. The only reason I'm sending this back is I do not think the camera is up to scratch.  I had a Samsung S9 and thought I'd try something new. I have since got the Samsung S10 to replace this phone. Confused??So here is what I think, and I'm comparing this to the Samsung S10.  The realme feels a little weightier and a little thicker than the Samsung S10, but for this, I actually think it feels more premium. The screen on the realme is beautiful, again, superior to the S10.  The thing that really stands out about the REALME XPRO 50 is the speed and smoothness of the PHONE. Navigating the app screens, opening apps and general use is blisteringly fast! It wipes the floor with the Samsung s10. This should be expected with the hardware in the phone, but it is noticeably superior - by far!I personally prefer the flat screen to the curved screen.  I feel perhaps the novelty of the curved screen is exactly that.The battery charging is also absolutely incredible. Full charge from 0% in a little over 30 minutes - incredible.Comes with screen protector and case.I purchased the moss green colour and it looks great. Again, largely personal choice, but it is classy not tacky.So why send back? The camera.  I just don't think the photo quality lives up to the rest of the phone.  For quick point and shoot, the Samsung S10 does beat the x50 pro in my opinion. The front facing selfie camera particularly is weak in anything other than bright light conditions.  The main camera can take nice pics in both bright light and low light though, but not reliably enough.I would never rely on a phone camera for those extra special occasions, but the phone camera quality is still one of the most important things on a smart phone for me.So I have decided to send my XPRO 50 back, purely on the camera quality being less than I wished it to be.  And I truly feel sad about this, because in absolutely every other aspect, this phone wipes the floor with every other phone I've ever owned.The minute I see a newer version of this phine that can compete with huawei/samsung/apple on reliable photography, then I will definitely be going back to realme in a flash.This phone in every other regard is fantastic.  So if you are not as fussy as me on the camera, then this phone will be incredibly hard to beat.As for me, I'm hoping the consolation of the Samsung S10's slightly better camera will provide adequate consolation for the myriad of things it cant compete with the x50 pro on!And if I shed a tear for those things, at least the Samsung is waterproof (something else the x50 pro doesn't boast).Hope this helps some of you decide.

Read more"}, {'Reviewer': 'John Doe', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in Germany on 29 March 2019', 'Review': 'Bevor ich zur eigentlichen Rezension komme, würde ich gerne noch ein paar Angaben zur Technik machen:Beim Nokia 5.1 Plus handelt es sich um die internationale Version des Nokia X5, das schon länger in China erhältlich ist. Beide Telefone sind baugleich, jedoch gibt es einen kleinen Unterschied betreffend den Prozessor: während das X5 nämlich acht Kerne, die mit bis zu 2 GHz takten, besitzt, hat Nokia die Entscheidung getroffen beim 5.1 Plus zwar denselben Prozessor mit acht Kernen, den Mediatek Helio P60, zu verbauen, der jedoch hier mit nur mit maximal 1.80 GHz taktet.Warum das so ist, bleibt wohl ein Geheimnis von Nokia.Ansonsten sind X5 und 5.1 Plus identisch, außer dass eben die unterstützten LTE Bänder an die lokalen Gegebenehiten angepasst wurden.Im alltäglichen Gebrauch wird der Unterschied zwischen X5 und 5.1 Plus wahrscheinlich nicht spürbar sein und trotzdem ist die Frage nach dem Warum berechtigt.Bei der Kamera setzt Nokia auf eine 13 MP Hauptkamera, die von einer 5 MP Kamera zwecks Tiefenbestimmung unterstützt wird. Die Frontkamera hat eine maximlae Auflösung von 8 MP.Das Display ist leider kein Full-HD sondern nur ein HD+ mit einer Auflösung von 720 x 1520 Pixel (287 ppi). Die Displaygröße ist 14,73 cm (5,80 Zoll), fühlt sich jedoch kleiner an.Das Nokia 5.1 Plus wird ausgeliefert mit Android 8.1 (Oreo) aktualisiert sich jedoch sofort (Stand: Ende März 2019) auf Android 9 (Pie) (Sicherheitspatch März 2019).Vom Äusseren ist das Nokia sehr gut verarbeitet, hat eine Glasrückseite (Achtung rutschig, Hülle empfehlenswert aber nicht im Lieferumfang enthalten), die Druckpunkte der seitlichen Tasten ist top und das Telefon macht einen wertigen Eindruck.Das Display ist schön hell und auch wenn die Auflösung "nur" HD+ ist, sind keine Pixel zu erkennen, das Display ist gut wenn auch natürlich nicht mit Topsmartphones zu vergleichen. Diese kosten dann aber auch ein Vielfaches vom Nokia 5.1 Plus.Nicht unerwähnt sollte auch die Notch sein; das Nokia 5.1 Plus besitzt eine Notch, die jedoch von Werk aus ausgeschaltet ist und sich bis jetzt (im Gegenteil zum X5 oder zum 5.1 Plus in Indien) auch nicht einschalten lässt. Auch hier bleibt Nokia eine Begründung schuldig.Die Kamera macht anständige Fotos, ohne dabei natürlich an die Qualität höherpreisigen Kameras aus Topsmartphones ranzukommen!Zu dem Preis von Knapp 180 Euro kann man das jedoch auch nicht verlangen (übrigens sind die Linsen nicht von ZEISS, der Hersteller ist mir jedoch nicht bekannt).Die Performance ist flüssig, Stockandroid sei Dank. Für alltägliche Aufgaben ist das Nokia 5.1 Plus trotz der eher mageren 3GB RAM vollkommen ausreichend!Ruckler hatte ich bisher keine. Auch die meisten Spiele laufen flüssig, bei aktuellen, grafikintensiven Spielenckann es jedoch zu kleinen Gedenksekunden kommen. Auch hier muss man sich bewusst sein, dass man ein Mittelklassetelefon und kein Premiumgerät hat.Alles in allem bin ich sehr zufrieden mit dem Gerät, es ist kompakt trotz des großen Displays und die Performance ist sehr gut.Ich habe das Nokia 5.1 Plus eigentlich als Zweitgerät gekauft, mittlerweile nutze ich es jedoch so gerne (vor allem dank der kompakten Bauform und des hochwertigen Designs), dass mein Haupttelefon öfters zu Hause bleibt.Hier noch ein paar zusätzliche positive Punkte:- guter Fingerprintsensor, reagiert schnell- Face Unlock verfügbar, reagiert gut (ausser bei sehr schlechtem Licht)- erweiterbarer Speicher mittels Micro-SD Karte- Android One- 3,5 mm KlinkenbüchseNegativ aufgefallen sind mir:- Hybridslot für entweder SD-Karte ODER zusätzliche SIM-Karte- Slot nur aus Plastik, nicht aus Metall- Fotos bei schlechten Lichtverhältnissen nur ausreichend- "nur" 3 GB Ram, wahrscheinlich in Zukunft schon obsolet- nur Bluetooth 4.2- keine Hülle im Lieferumfang enthalten- Notch nicht aktivierbar obwohl vorhandenBeim Nokia 5.1 Plus macht Nokia vieles richtig, liefert ein schönes Gerät, das flüssig läuft und dank des Android One Programms auch noch viele Jahre aktuell sein wird. Die Kamera entspricht den Erwartungen an ein Gerät dieser Preisklasse und das Design mit Glasrückseite lässt eher auf ein höherpreisiges Gerät schlussfolgern.Einzig der begrenzte RAM Speicher von 3 GB könnte in Zukunft an seine Grenzen stossen, hier wären mindestens 4 GB löblich gewesen.Trotzdem spreche ich eine klare Kaufempfehlung für jeden, der viel Smartphone zum günstigen Preis haben möchte, aus.

reviews:
[{'Reviewer': 'Amazon Customer', 'Rating': '1.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in the United States on 20 April 2019', 'Review': 'Phone does not work unless in roaming wich is limited depending upon your carrier and plan so usually runs out after a day or two of normal usage them the phone is useless for 28 days made multiple attempts to resolve the issue over weeks with no progress and what seems to be very little effort on their end.
Read more'}, {'Reviewer': 'Prem k.', 'Rating': '4.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in India on 12 August 2019', 'Review': "HIGHLIGHTSThe Samsung Galaxy M10 is priced at Rs. 7,990 onwardsYou get a waterdrop-style notch and dual rear camerasBattery life is great, but the performance is sub-parDespite the onslaught of affordable smartphones made by brands from China and beyond, India continues to have a love affair with Samsung. The Korean manufacturer has been selling its phones in the country for a long time, manufactures many of its devices in India itself, and has a fair amount of goodwill thanks to its excellent dealer and service networks. Therefore, any affordable option from Samsung needs to be taken seriously.Enter the Samsung Galaxy M10, a smartphone that is incredibly fresh and different from what we've come to expect from Samsung. The company previously shunned the idea of the notch, but the Samsung Galaxy M10 and slightly more expensive Galaxy M20 are the company's first phones to sport this element. While the notch itself might be considered a disruptive design element, the idea of the notch is to allow a screen that occupies more of the front, and that's the look Samsung is going for here. We've put the new Samsung Galaxy M10 through its paces, and here's our review.Samsung Galaxy M10 designThe highlight of the Samsung Galaxy M10 is its screen, with its waterdrop-style notch at the top for the front camera. Just above the camera on the top edge sits the earpiece, and the entire thing looks similar to what we've seen on smartphones such as the OnePlus 6T and Oppo F9 Pro. A thin black border can be seen all around the screen, with it stretching almost till the top edge and leaving a narrow chin area at the bottom.The back and sides of the Samsung Galaxy M10 are plastic, with curved edges and corners. The ports and buttons are all where we expected them to be, and the only thing that really stood out was the speaker grille at the back rather than at the bottom. This was common a few years ago, but now comes across as odd. It also causes audio to be slightly muffled when the phone is lying flat on its back, which can affect how loud the ringtone is.The top-left corner of the back of the phone has the dual-camera setup and flash, and you'll also see a Samsung logo and some regulatory text. The blue colour of our review unit looked good, but the plastic was prone to picking up fingerprints and smudges.Something that a lot of users will appreciate on the device is the SIM and external storage tray, which features dedicated slots for two Nano-SIM cards and a microSD card. It's also worth pointing out that the Samsung Galaxy M10 doesn't have a fingerprint sensor, and you only have face recognition as a method of biometric security on the device.The screen on the phone is a 6.22-inch HD+ resolution ‘Infinity-V' TFT display, named so because of the shape of the notch. Perhaps its biggest issue is the resolution; at 720x1520 pixels, you get a 19:9 aspect ratio but it isn't very sharp. For basic usage, we didn't have too many issues, particularly with apps such as WhatsApp or anything that doesn't rely on heavy visuals.AdvertisementThe Samsung Experience UI looks alright even with the lower resolution, although we could see some grain around the app icons. However, we weren't impressed with the screen when using it with Netflix and simple games such as Subway Surfers.We also didn't quite like the colours and brightness, and found that things don't look very good at wider viewing angles. Furthermore, the screen appears dull unless you drag the brightness slider all the way to the maximum level. What we did like about the screen was its size, proportions, and edge-to-edge design.Samsung Galaxy M10 specifications and softwareWhen it comes to specifications, the Samsung Galaxy M10 comes across as a bit disappointing. Under the hood is the Exynos 7870 1.6GHz octa-core SoC, a processor that was first seen on the Samsung Galaxy J7 (2016), which was released roughly two and a half years ago.Fabricated on the 14nm process, this SoC was decent at the time of its launch but hasn't aged as well as competing SoCs from Qualcomm such as the Snapdragon 625. You get either 2GB or 3GB of RAM and either 16GB or 32GB of internal storage, as well as dual-VoLTE connectivity. Our review unit was the higher variant with 3GB of RAM and 32GB of storage, priced at Rs. 8,990, with the other variant Rs. 1,000 cheaper.You also get a 3,400mAh battery and a 5W charger in the box. While the battery capacity is acceptable given the price and specifications of the phone, the charger isn't nearly as fast as it should be. During our testing it took a little over three hours to fully charge the device. The phone also uses the dated Micro-USB standard for charging and data transfers. A 3.5mm headphone socket lets you connect wired headphones to the phone.The Samsung Galaxy M10 runs on Android 8.1 Oreo, with the Samsung Experience 9.5 UI on top. For anyone familiar with the software on Samsung's phones, the Galaxy M10's UI is just what you'd expect. While Samsung's smartphone software has improved of late, there is still a fair amount of bloat to contend with. Preinstalled on the phone are a handful of Samsung's system apps, some Microsoft apps, and Daily Hunt. Not all of these can be uninstalled, which can be bothersome in the long run, especially on the lower variant with 16GB of internal storage.A couple of interesting aspects include the lock screen Stories feature and the dual-messenger feature. The former shows you different images on the lock screen which often have to do with current events and news (but also a few ads), while the latter lets you have two instances of popular apps such as WhatsApp so you can use two different accounts on the same device.The Samsung Galaxy M10 features face recognition, but we found ourselves better off using a PIN or no security at all. The face recognition feature took a few seconds to unlock the phone each time we tried it, and often failed even in good lighting conditions.Samsung Galaxy M10 performance and battery lifeWith a dated processor, the Samsung Galaxy M10 is disappointing when it comes to performance. Apart from the slow face recognition, there are considerable delays in various other simple functions, such as switching from the camera to the gallery to view pictures we had just shot, reloading some background apps, and quick multi-tasking when we needed to switch between apps. We often even noticed a slight delay in responsiveness to taps within the UI itself, such as in the Settings app.3GB of RAM and 32GB of storage is now what we'd expect from a sub-Rs. 10,000 smartphone, and Samsung has delivered this on the variant priced at Rs. 8,990. You can run most popular apps, including instant messaging, social media services, and basic games without much trouble once they've loaded up. We did try to run PUBG Mobile on the phone, and the experience was expectedly poor with plenty of performance issues even at the lowest graphics settings.Putting the Samsung Galaxy M10 through our usual suite of benchmarking tools, we got results that were in line with the dated SoC. AnTuTu produced a score of 64,371, while Geekbench returned a single-core score of 728 and a multi-core score of 3,674. These numbers might have been good enough for a mid-range smartphone back in 2016, but serve as adequate evidence of the Galaxy M10's poor performance in 2019. Even the graphical benchmark tests returned scores that were lower than those of the similarly priced Realme C1 (Review).We put the Samsung Galaxy M10 through our HD video loop battery test and got a screen time of 14 hours and 29 minutes with a full charge of the 3,400mAh battery. The HD+ resolution of the screen and power-efficient processor can be credited with the good battery life, and we saw a similar level of efficiency even in day-to-day usage.With basic usage that included having a single SIM card connected to an LTE network, taking a few photos, streaming some Netflix video, and playing a few basic games, the phone easily lasted through the day with plenty of power left to carry through till around noon of the next day. As mentioned, the only drawback in this aspect is the slow charging.Samsung Galaxy M10 camerasThe Samsung Galaxy M10 features a dual-camera setup at the rear, comprised of a 13-megapixel main sensor with an f/1.9 aperture and a 5-megapixel secondary sensor with an f/2.2 aperture. The second camera enables ultra-wide angle photography, and can be selected through the camera app on the smartphone. You also get a 5-megapixel f/2.0 front camera, with both the front and rear cameras capable of recording full-HD video.The primary rear camera on the Samsung Galaxy M10 isn't bad by any means considering the price of the device, but it isn't very good either. Photos taken with the Samsung Galaxy M10 are good at first glance, but looking closely shows some grain and lack of detail. Furthermore, colours are a bit dull, and the photos appear a bit darker than the actual scenes photographed.The wide-angle camera lets you take some interesting pictures that capture a wider frame, making for good landscape shots over distances. Although the images will still appear a bit dull, the extra room in the frame can add some character to images. However, as is the case with all wide-angle cameras, the edges of the frame will show some warping.Low-light performance can be alright when shooting macro images and close-ups, but with subjects at a distance, you'll see a lot of grain in the images. Further, brightly lit parts of the image (such as street lights or lamps) tend to get overexposed.Video looks decent, but the lack of stabilisation means that any video taken while moving will capture all the shakes. The front camera is alright as well, and adequate for video calls or the occasional selfie. On the whole, the camera setup on the Samsung Galaxy M10 is acceptable for the price, but you shouldn't expect too much from this phone.VerdictAt Rs. 7,990 onwards, the Samsung Galaxy M10 is among Samsung's most affordable smartphones today. There are some big pros to this device, including its modern design and  a battery that will keep the phone going for well over a day with normal usage. Most of all, it's an affordable Samsung phone, which in itself makes this device important.However, this budget smartphone is far from perfect. The excellent battery life is a result of two big letdowns  the HD+ resolution screen and the dated SoC. While the shape and dimensions of the screen give this phone its modern look, the quality isn't quite as good as we'd have liked. Furthermore, performance on this device is below average, and the camera doesn't achieve a lot beyond its key feature of ultra-wide-angle photography.The Samsung Galaxy M10 is a device for Samsung fans who are looking for a phone with a modern design, but options such as the Realme C1 (Review) and Xiaomi Redmi 6 (Review) are, in our opinion, more rounded devices at around the same price. If you do go for the Samsung Galaxy M10, we recommend that you get the 3GB RAM/ 32GB storage variant.

Read more'}, {'Reviewer': 'Marco', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in Germany on 10 January 2019', 'Review': "Da ich dringend ein neues Handy benötigt habe, da mein HTC10 nach etwas mehr als zwei Jahren den Geist aufgegeben hat, habe ich mich kurerhand dafür entschieden sowohl das Huawei P20 als auch das Xiaomi Mi8 zu testen. Gewonnen hat hierbei definitiv das Xiaomi Mi8. Das P20 (obwohl dessen UVP wesentlich höher angesiedelt ist als die des Xiaomi's) wirkt in so vielen Bereichen nicht gut umgesetzt. Vor allem hat mich das Display gestört, hier bin ich beim Xiaomi definitiv mehr als zufrieden.+Trotz der Pentile Matrix ist das Display sehr scharf, die Farben sind nicht übersättigt, aber definitiv sehr viel satter als beim blassen Huawei Display (gegen dieses sieht selbst mein HTC von 2016 besser aus).+Die Gesichtserkennung funktioniert so rasend schnell (Region auf bspw. Italien stellen und schon funktioniert das ganze), dass ich den Fingerabdruckscanner eigentlich nicht mehr nutze. Selbst bei völliger Dunkelheit erkennt das Xiaomi das Gesicht und entsperrt ohne verzögerung. Das liegt wohl vor allem daran, dass eine infrarotkamera plus Infrarotlicht genutzt wird. Deshalb ist für mich die breite Notch auch vernachlässigbar, da zumindest der Platz sinnvoll genutzt wurde.+Die Bildqualität liegt ein wenig unterhalb der des P20, sollte jedoch für alle Anwendungszwecke mehr als  ausreichend sein. Hier lege ich persönlich den geringsten Wert, da ich wenn dann mit einer richtigen Kamera fotografiere und das Handy nur für Schnappschüsse brauche.-Die Tonqualität ist gut, kommt nicht an HTC Boomsound heran, liegt aber auf ähnlichem Niveau wie die des P20.+Der Prozessor ist auch schneller als der Kirin 970 und die Benutzeroberfläche reagiert auch zackig schnell wie bei einem HTC.+Der Akku hält auch länger als das P20 bei mir. Mindestens 24 Stunden bei intensiver nutzung, normale Nutzung z.b. bei einem Arbeitstag dann bis ca 48 Stunden Laufzeit.Für die UVP von umgerechnet weniger als 350€ kann ich nichts gravierend negatives feststellen.
Read more"}]

The screen looks great for the size, and Android One is clean, simple and fast.Compared to a couple years ago, you're getting a lot for $160. That is what I expected.The diagonal measurement of the usable display of my phone is 5.375 inches.
Read more'}, {'Reviewer': 'Elax46', 'Rating': '5.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in Italy on 6 October 2018', 'Review': 'Lo scorso anno mi sono trovato a criticare pesantemente il Huawei P10. Le cose quest’anno sono cambiate visto il netto miglioramento del produttore cinese sotto molti punti di vista, dopo un ottimo Mate 10 Pro, Huawei punta tutto su questo P20 Pro focalizzandosi principalmente su due aspetti: qualità fotografica e esperienza multimediale, adesso vi spiego tutto all'interno della recensione.Materiali e Design: ben fatto Huawei!Vista la riduzione al minimo della cornice superiore per mantenere alcuni elementi essenziali è inevitabile la presenza del notch, che possiamo anche nascondere tramite il software.La scocca è realizzata in vetro con angoli smussati che facilitano l’impugnatura del dispositivo. L’ergonomia tutto sommato è buona anche se il vetro lo rende scivoloso. La parte bassa, del frontale, è praticamente scopiazzata al Honor View 10.Huawei ha puntato molto anche sulle varianti cromatiche, questa Midnight Blue fa la sua bella figura, inoltre cambia sfumatura a seconda della diversa incidenza della luce. Huawei ha puntato molto sulla variante Twilight portando anche un innovazione per quanto riguarda le colorazioni, sono curioso di sapere quale sarà la variante cromatica più venduta, anche se mi sembra scontato.Il lettore delle impronte frontale resta a mio avviso la migliore soluzione da un punto di vista pratico, anche se diventa antiestetico, anche in questo caso si comporta sempre egregiamente sbloccando il device 8 volte su 10. Con questo P20 Pro ho usato principalmente lo sblocco con il volto visto che funziona molto bene in qualsiasi condizione di luce, a patto che manteniate la giusta distanza dal volto.Display: OLED Full HD+, la migliore scelta!Il miglior compromesso trà qualità e consumi e proprio il display che ha integrato huawei su questo device: Full HD+ di tipo OLED con 408 ppi. La qualità del pannello è buona con ottimi angoli di visuale e dei colori tendenti a tonalità fredde, ma possiamo comunque modificare la temperatura colore all’interno delle impostazioni.Gli angoli di visuale sono buoni con un contrasto eccellente e neri molto profondi come tutti gli OLED. Inoltre all’interno delle impostazioni e possibile andare a nascondere il notch.Tramite l’analisi, con il colorimetro, ho riscontato un Delta E non molto positivo per i colori primari e la scala di grigi ( il valore 3 è il massimo sotto cui stare) . I nis raggiunti sono ben 432 mentre la copertura sRGB è del 134.2%.Hardware: Kirin 970 fa il suo dovereHuawei non ha realizzato una nuova piattaforma hardware per questo P20 Pro mi si è affidata al buon Kirin 970 ulteriormente ottimizzato con Android 8.1. Come per tutti i top di gamma la fluidità è ottima, nell’apertura delle pagine web. Resto dell’idea che 6GB di RAM non servono a molto, ma qui ci sono e rappresentano una marcia in più per sfruttare al meglio il system on chip. La gestione della RAM e discreta con un utilizzo medio del 57%.La piattaforma hardware è la diretta concorrente della controparte Exynos e Qualcomm ma se la cava egregiamente. Peccato per la presenza del Bluetooth in versione 4.2 rispetto all’attuale 5.0.Le prestazioni delle GPU sono scontate, vista la potenza della Mali-G72. Tutti i titoli anche quelli che richiedono un maggiore sforzo dell’hardware si comportano in maniera eccellente.Le temperature registrate, con la camera termica, raggiungono picchi di 45 gradi sotto bencmark nulla di particolarmente preoccupante anche se con lunghe sessioni di gioco il calore al tatto da un po fastidio.Batteria, Audio e Ricezione:L’autonomia di questo P20 Pro è ottima si riesce tranquillamente a raggiungere le quasi 5 ore di schermo attivo e in giornate con un uso medio si riesce anche coprire due giorni di utilizzo. Come sempre il discorso batteria è molto soggettivo ma questa 4000 mAh si comporta in modo egregio.Anche Huawei segue gli altri produttori con la possibilità di godere di un audio stereo andando a sfruttare anche la capsula auricolare. La qualità audio è decisamente superiore inoltre, il sistema, è in grado di variare la consistenza del suono rispetto all'orientamento dello smartphone (verticale/orizzontale). La ricezione si comporta molto bene come il GPS.FotocamereIl compatto fotografico, sulla carta, è impressionante. L’ottica principale è una 40 megapixel ƒ/1.8 RGB e sensore secondario in bianco e nero da 20 megapixel e apertura ƒ/1.6 ma troviamo anche un terzo sensore di tipo tele, zoom 3x,  con apertura ƒ/2.4 da 8 megapixel e stabilizzazione ottica.A 40 megapixel non è possibile effettuare alcun tipo di zoom e  il software non ci permetta di passare automaticamente a 10 megapixel per sfruttare lo zoom ottico, un tocco di praticità in più poteva starci.Parto analizzando le foto scattate a 40 megapixel. Tralasciando i dati tecnici, il livello del dettaglio offerto da questo sensore supera di gran lunga tutti gli altri top di gamma. Questo è associato ad un ottimo bilanciamento del bianco e una eccellente esposizione.Andando ad effetturare un crop sulle immagini si riescono a scorgere dettagli molto ben visibili e senza alcun tipo di rumore, cosa impossibile con una risoluzione più bassa. La terza fotocamera tele è la vera novità per Huawei visto che in questi anni ha scelto sempre di affiancare il sensore monocromatico. Questo tipo di ottica ci permette di avere una visione diversa grazie ad una profondità di campo differente. Certo il livello del dettaglio non è il massimo, soprattutto a 5x.Gli scatti in condizioni di scarsa illuminazione hanno sempre messo in crisi gli smartphone ed è proprio in questo ambito che un vero top di gamma si distingue. Huawei ha creato una modalità ad hoc chiamata notte. Sostanzialmente è possibile sfruttare una lunga esposizione, con una conseguente acquisizione di maggior luce, con l’importante supporto della stabilizzazione.La qualità degli scatti è ottima anche se ci sono dei contro in quanto si va a perdere la rapidità di scatto. Aspettare quei 7 secondi ( 4 per l’esposizione e 3 per l’elaborazione software ) non ci permette di effettuare degli scatti al voloLa fotocamera anteriore è una 24 Megapixel ed è quella che mi ha convinto meno. La qualità degli scatti e buona ma tende molo a sovraesporre i soggetti. Inoltre in alcuni casi si percepisce una messa a fuoco non perfetta.Video: non ci siamo per niente!Considerando la qualità riscontrata nel compatto fotografico mi sarei aspettato un risultato analogo anche per i video ma purtroppo mi sbagliavo. La risoluzione massima di registrazione è il 4k a 30 fps ma in questo caso non è possibile sfruttare la stabilizzazione elettronica EIS, che Huawei ha tanto elogiato in fase di presentazione, quest’ultima non può essere utilizzata neanche a 60fps in full HD ma solo a 1080p a 30 fps.Un limite molto importante per un top di gamma considerando anche che la concorrenza ci permette di spingerci al 4K a 60fps e con tanto di stabilizzazione ottica.Inoltre è possibile anche registrare video in slow motion a 960 fps e qui la presenza della stabilizzazione si fa sentire.Il software non ci permette di passare, durante la registrazione, all'ottica tele con la classica icona 3x. Il passaggio è comunque possibile tramite il classico  pinch-to-zoom ma questo crea fastidiosi scatti alla registrazione, speriamo che huawei metta una pezza con futuri aggiornamenti software.ConclusioniTirare le somme su questo P20 Pro è molto difficile visto che al momento incarna tutte le caratteristiche del miglior top di gamma sulla piazza. Il limite più importante resta la registrazione video, per niente all'altezza di un device top, e una fotocamera frontale che non mi ha molto convinto. In un 2018, dove Samsung ha fatto un piccolo passo in avanti con il suo S9, Huawei fa un bel balzo in avanti con questo P20 Pro che vanta il miglior compatto fotografico del momento, un autonomia eccellente e prestazioni ai massimi livelli. Non tollero molto la somiglianza con Honor View 10 visto che si tratta di un prodotto di fascia inferiore a questo P20 Pro e soprattutto perchè un acquirente di questo device si aspetta un prodotto con un design "nuovo" e non con alcune piccole scopiazzature da altri prodotti. Il prezzo di listino di questo P20 Pro è alto, 899 euro, anche se già lo si trova sotto i 600 euro. Questo smartphone conferma ancora che tra midrange e top di gamma continua ad esserci una netta differenza, certo le prestazioni sono pressoché simili ma tutte queste piccole funzioni avanzate fanno la differenza. Il claim pubblicitario di questo P20 Pro è "un nuovo rinascimento della fotografia" mi sa che Huawei, a questo giro, ci è riuscita alla grande.
Read more'}, {'Reviewer': 'Kanza Makour', 'Rating': '1.0 ', 'Date': 'Reviewed in the United States on 25 September 2023', 'Review': 'I’m having problems with it after 1 month only, the screen starting to show black spots, and I can’t return now I just lost my moneys.Update: after 2 months the screen became black, the phone is trash
